By analyzing the genome of 9,000 people, Hamburgers and Swiss scientists want to find out more about the causes of cardiovascular diseases.
The research project is the largest of its kind in the German-speaking area, the University Hospital Hamburg-Eppendorf (UKE) announced on Friday. The Kuehne Foundation is funding the project with 12.5 million euros. From Switzerland, the Davos High Mountain Hospital, which belongs to the foundation, and the University Hospital Zurich are involved.
Obesity, smoking and unhealthy diets are among the key influencing risk factors for cardiovascular disease. Genetic factors help determine the risk. However, the interaction between genes and external influences is insufficiently known, it said. Now the scientists want to compare the entire genome of 8,000 healthy people with that of 1,000 former patients of the University Heart and Vascular Center at UKE.
Currently, more than 4,000 of the approximately 20,000 relevant human genes are known to cause possible disease-causing changes in DNA - so-called mutations -, according to the clinic, about 200 would be added each year.
According to the initiators, the aim of the five-year project is to develop new options for the prevention, detection and treatment of cardiac arrhythmias, heart failure and heart attacks. The data could also be useful in researching other popular diseases, according to Stefan Blankenberg, head of the University Heart and Vascular Center. New findings on the interaction between heart and brain, heart and kidney as well as cancer are possible.
The chairman of the Kühne Foundation, Klaus-Michael Kühne (82), also stressed that there is a firm will to use the data for the research of other diseases. The clinic of the foundation in Davos deals with mainly allergies. Now a Center for Cardiovascular Precision Medicine is to be created on the medical campus there, and a professorship for bioinformatics in Hamburg has been created very gratefully.
The biosamples of the healthy participants come from Hamburgers who also participate in the "Hamburg City Health Study". With 45,000 subjects, this is the largest local health study in the world, according to the clinic. In the genetic decryption, strict attention is paid to the protection of the anonymized data, the scientists assured. It is about a petabyte (1000 terabyte) of data, said Holger Mochs University of Zurich.
According to the UKE, a person’s genetic material can now be decoded within 24 hours. The mere material cost would be 1300 euros. The first gene sequencing worldwide, the results of which were published in 2001, cost several hundred million euros. The study is expected to start on 1 October, and all 9,000 samples are to be analysed by the end of 2020. First results are expected in the year after.
