Doping: Further Russian manipulations proven
Material from the Moscow analysis lab is being manipulated - this is confirmed by David Howman, former director of the World Anti-Doping Agency (Wada) and today's integrity chief of the World Athletics Association.
At the start of the World Championship in Athletics, new details of the doping scandal in Russia are revealed - and they destroy the little credibility that Russian sport had gained back at the beginning of the year and even only on its own. In January 2019, the Moscow Doping Laboratory finally delivered the required samples from 2012 to 2015 to the World Anti-Doping Agency (Wada).
In December 2014, systematic fraud in Russian sports had been revealed. After this, the Russian football team had blocked the Russian anti-doping agency (Russia) for three years. During this time, Russian athletes were not completely banned from the world stage. The International Olympic Committee left after individual examination at the 2016 Summer Games in Rio. In February 2018, around 270 athletes of the country competed in the sports under a neutral flag.
Positive findings are missing
The following September, the Wada repealed the Rusada ban, but demanded access to the laboratory and the said samples. The data should provide information on the extent of the cover-up of doping cases in state doping. They should help to punish athletes afterwards. Three months later, they were finally delivered.
However, the Chairman of the Independent Integrity Commission (AIU) of the World Athletics Association (IAAF) has now confirmed that the doping data from the Moscow analysis laboratory has been manipulated. "Yes. We received the data nine months ago. We should check whether the Task Force has received the correct data," David Howman said in an interview with the "Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung" of Friday.
The World Cup is not affected
This confirms the attitude of the IAAF: The athletics federation is the only organization to hold on to Russia’s ban. At the World Cup in Doha, 30 Russian athletes under a neutral flag started. They had to prove that they were training outside the Russian system and undergo testing.
Earlier this week, the Wada had already put manipulations in the room and asked Russia to respond to the allegations within three weeks, now threatening the renewed ban on Rusada and, in the worst case, the exclusion from the 2020 Tokyo Olympics.
